dataIdInfo.idAbs: Fire history reports by date and organization: 1980 to 2016
dataIdInfo.idPurp: The purpose of this geospatial data is to provide a depiction of federal fire occurrence reports for use in GIS analysis.

Consts.useLimit: No attempt was made to determine the accuracy of the latitude/longitude coordinates of the reports that fell within the land boundaries of the us as depicted in the statesp020 shapefile from the USGS National Atlas. Therefore, the user is cautioned to examine the accuracy of the location of the data before utilizing it in any GIS analysis.

Natural fire causes involve fires caused without direct human intervention, such as lightning, earthquake, wind, and the like.

attr.attrdef: The assignment of a wildfire to a category according to its size

Fire Type 1 (10’s digit) are all wildland fires where the appropriate fire management response was taken, excluding natural outs, support actions, and fuels management activities. Fire Type 2 (10’s digit) are all wildland fires discovered that have been extinguished by natural causes prior to initiation of suppression action; excluding fires for which aerial or ground monitoring is deemed the appropriate fire management responses. Fire Type 3 (10’s digit) is action taken on a fire which is not threatening federal lands and no formal agreement exists which would require a federal fire response other than a mutual aid agreement. Fire Type 4 (10’s digit) are all fires or mechanical treatments necessary to reduce fuels as a precursor to the introduction of fire or when the hazards of using fire would be excessive, used to meet approved land management objectives. Fire Type 5 (10’s digit) (False Alarms) are for reported fires on which some type of response was initiated but no suppression action took place. Fire Type 6 (10’s digit) are projects using funds assigned from a fire severity account. Protection Type 1 (1’s digit) – Bureau land protected by that bureau Protection Type 2 (1’s digit) – Bureau land protected by another federal agency or bureau under a cooperative agreement. Protection Type 3 (1’s digit) – Bureau land protected by another non-federal agency under a cooperative agreement Protection Type 4 (1's digit) – A Bureau that takes a confine and contain action of a fire on their land Protection Type 5 (1’s digit) – Other land not under cooperative agreement or contract where action is taken by the bureau to prevent spread onto their bureau land. Protection Type 6 (1’s digit) – Other land protected by the bureau under a cooperative agreement or contract. Protection Type 7 (1’s digit) – Support actions by the bureau on wildland fires. Protection Type 8 (1’s digit) – Prescribed fires Protection Type 9 (1’s digit) – Where the appropriate fire management response was based on objectives from an approved NEPA document. Protection Type A (1's digit) - BLM land (point of origin) independent of protection responsibility Protection Type B (1’s digit) – Other Land (non-BLM point of origin) BLM Response Legally Required Protection Type C (1’s digit) – (AK) Other Land (non-BLM point of origin) BLM Response Legally Required Protection Type D (1’s digit) – Other Land (non-BLM point of origin) BLM land burns Protection Type E (1's digit) - Agency responds to a reported wildland fire...(fire not found/did not occur)

dataLineage.statement: The federal fire occurrence dataset comes from WFMI, FMIS, and FIRESTAT. The entire dataset for WFMI from 1980 to 2016 was updated. For FMIS, the last 10-years were updated and for FIRESTAT just 2016.

dataSource.srcDesc: WFMI - Wildland Fire Management Information System. (BIA, BLM, NPS) FMIS - Fire Management Information System (FWS) FIRESTAT - Fire Statistics System (USFS)

srcCitatn.resTitle: Federal Fire Occurrence Data from 1980 to 2016

prcStep.stepDesc: FMIS, WFMI, and FIRESTAT data was uploaded into ArcGIS and then converted to the same format.
